Event detection and processing

Author: Srdjan Sarikas
Date: 29 Jan 2021

Basics

Single trace

So, we have a trace with events to detect:

roi = 226
regions.plot_trace(roi)

We estimate the events to be a few seconds long. So, filtering at a timescale of say 10s could produce a nice separation between the uninteresting component with features slower than 10s and a faster, interesting one.

ts = 10  # timescale
regions.fast_filter_traces(ts)
regions.plot_trace(roi, cols=["trace","slower_10","faster_10"])

Filtering also provides a z-score, aka standard score, of the signal. This measures the significance of a particular event in the units of standard deviation \(\sigma\). For example, \(z=2\) corresponds to a p-value of 0.025, while for \(z=3\), \(p_v\sim\)0.0015.

regions.fast_filter_traces(ts)
regions.plot_trace(roi, cols=["zScore_10"])

To detect excursions we see in the plot, we need to choose a threshold value for the zScore. A default value for this is 3, butt this trace is particularly prominent, so we can choose quite a high value, say \(z_{th} = 5\).

regions.detect_events(ts, z_th=5)

The result of this command is saved within the object itself and is just a pandas DataFrame:

print(regions.events["10"].head())

   height  halfwidth       t0  peakpoint  roi  ts
0   9.756      1.971  146.349      147.3  127  10
1   7.963      3.196  203.406      204.1  127  10
2   7.482      2.980  253.353      254.5  127  10
3   8.148      1.673  283.919      284.5  127  10
4   6.113      2.492  292.923      294.1  127  10

Each event is characterized by it height (in z-score), the width at the half of this height (halfwidth), and the timepoint when this is happens. There is also the time of the peak itself peakpoint (often, but not necessarily at the center of the peak), and of course what roi it refers to.

The basic command for plotting the events is

# I am presuming you have imported islets previously
islets.EventDistillery.plot_events(my_events)

We may want to plot the trace together with the events, but then we need pass the axes as an argument. Also, the default colormap above might not look great on white background, so we can choose another one.

ax_trace = regions.plot_trace(roi)
islets.EventDistillery.plot_events(my_events, ax=ax_trace, cmap="Greys_r")

The same function can be used to plot all detected events (my example here has only 35 rois, in general, it has much more)

islets.EventDistillery.plot_events(regions.events["10"])

You may want to examine the events more closely using the interactive app

# works only in jupyter notebook!
regions.examine_events(my_events, x="halfwidth", y="height")
# or a bit differently:
regions.examine_events(my_events, x="t0", y="halfwidth")
# you can also pass it all detected events:
regions.examine_events(regions.events["10"], x="t0", y="halfwidth")

An interesting static graph can also be obtained using native plotting library

regions.events["10"].plot.hexbin(
    x="t0",
    y="halfwidth",
    figsize=(14,4),
    )

For other useful options of the hexbin plot see its documentation. (For example, you might find the following options useful: mincnt=1, gridsize=(200,50), bins="log", cmap='hot')

Events processing

Let us go back to events of a single for a moment

my_events.plot.scatter(
    x="t0",
    y="halfwidth",
    figsize=(10,4),
    )

The first spike at around 75s is actually detected as two different events.

print(my_events.iloc[:2])

     height  halfwidth      t0  peakpoint  roi  ts
506   8.911      1.356  74.944       76.1  226  10
507  12.552      4.784  74.283       78.1  226  10

Depending on rigorousness of analysis, we may want to avoid this, and choose a single one to represent that spike. There is a function for that. For each detected event it checks whether there are other events which start and end around the same time. If yes, the two events are connected. This creates a network of connected event out of which the highest one is chosen, and the rest are discarded. The crucial parameter that retermines how close is close is called halfwidth_toll, and by default it has a value of 0.2. In this case, we can be very lenient and put it to one, meaning any events that starts and/or ends a halfwidth sooner or later should be merged.

my_events_distilled = islets.EventDistillery.distill_events_per_roi(my_events, regions, halfwidth_toll=1, take_best=True)[0]
# look, the short one at 75s is now gone:
print(my_events_distilled.head())

     height  halfwidth       t0  peakpoint  roi  ts     tend
507  12.552      4.784   74.283       78.1  226  10   79.067
508  12.244      2.073   83.546       84.5  226  10   85.620
509  11.176      2.195   91.308       92.5  226  10   93.504
510   9.826      1.521   98.890       99.7  226  10  100.411
511   9.849      2.366  146.293      147.3  226  10  148.659

We can then to the same for all the events

all_distilled = islets.EventDistillery.distill_events(regions.events["10"], regions, halfwidth_toll=1, take_best=True)

The result is again a data frame, and all hints above apply here too.

Events across different timescales

In general, we may be interested to investigate events accross many timescales.

candidateEvents = islets.EventDistillery.sequential_filtering(regions)
# this will produce very verbose output, but that's fine.

By default, the timescales are increasing multiplicatively, by a factor of \(2^{1/4}\).

Let us go back to our roi 226 and plot it, this time allowing the function to modify out dataframe and add two different columns that are useful for plotting

my_events_big = candidateEvents.query(f"roi=={roi}").copy()
islets.EventDistillery.plot_events(my_events_big, modify=True)

The added columns are color and coltrans (short for color transform). Namely, I wish the color to be representative of the halfwidth. For this, I first perform a non-linear transformation of the halfwidth onto a [0,1] interval, and then use that to define color.

my_events_big.plot.scatter(x="halfwidth",y="coltrans", c="color")

If you imported plt, you may also want to see the above graph in lin-log scale, by running plt.xscale("log"). (If you define coltrans and color yoursefl, running plot_events will use those values, and will not overwrite them.)

Let us see close up what can the distillation now do (run %matplotlib notebook first if you wish an interactive plot):

my_events_big_distilled = islets.EventDistillery.distill_events_per_roi(
    my_events_big,
    regions,
    plot=True,
)

It uncovers events at all scales simultaneusly. The top plot shows discarded events in categorical color, depending on the reason they were discarded. The middle plot shows all events, and the bottom plot the distilled ones, plotted at the height of the timescale they were discovered at. First, if there are events happening too close the boundaries of the time frame (within half the duration), they are discarded. The events are then connected according the procedure explained above. If the duration is shorter than 2s, all unconnected events are discarded; above that threshold there needs to be at least 4 connected events, for it not to be discarded. These parameters are called small_halfwidth, and minconfidence, and we can change them, just like the halfwidth_toll. For example, by putting small_halfwidth=10, and minconfidence=3, we could make the algorithm more lenient, by accepting groups with two events if they are 10s long, and require only three elements if they are longer. On the other end, by putting small_halfwidth=0, and minconfidence=5, we could make the algorithm very stringent, and require it accepts only events that are uncovered at at least 5 timescales, no matter how long they last.

Finally, we can run the procedure for all

Events = islets.EventDistillery.distill_events(candidateEvents, regions)

This function can take all the same arguments as discussed for distill_events_per_roi. This may take some time, so I suggest you first run distill_events_per_roi for several rois of your choice, to convince yourself the distillation behaves as intended, and tweak parameters if necessary, before running it for all rois.

Finally, you may want to plot events

islets.EventDistillery.plot_events(Events)

and save

# as csv
Events.to_csv("path_to_filename.csv", index=False)
# or as excel
Events.to_excel("path_to_filename.xlsx", index=False)

FWIW, to read a dataframe from a file, you can use

Events = pd.read_csv("path_to_filename.csv") # for csv
Events = pd.read_excel("path_to_filename.xlsx") # for excel
